496.title: Square visualization of probabilities on two events
496.text: $$ \newcommand{\true}{\text{True}} \newcommand{\false}{\text{False}} \newcommand{\bP}{\mathbb{P}} $$ Say we have two events $A$ and $B$ and a probability distribution $\bP$ over whether or not they happen. We can represent $\bP$ as a square: So for example, the probability $\bP(A,B)$ of both $A$ and $B$ occurring is the ratio of the areas of the dark red region and the entire square: Notice that in the above square, the reddish blocks for $\bP(A,B)$ and $\bP(A,\neg B)$ are the same width and form a column; and likewise the blueish blocks for $\bP(\neg A,B)$ and $\bP(\neg A,\neg B)$. This is because we chose to [factoring_probability factor] our probability distribution starting with $A$: $$\bP(A,B) = \bP(A) \bP( B \mid A)\ .$$ More precisely, for any choice of truth values $b_A \in \{\true, \false\}$ and $b_B \in \{\true, \false\}$, we have $$\bP(A = b_A,B= b_B) = \bP(A= b_A) \bP( B= b_B \mid A= b_A)\ .$$ (We're using the equivalence between events and binary random variables.) So the first factor $\bP(A = b_A)$ tells us how wide to make the first column relative to the second column, and then the second factor $\bP( B= b_B \mid A= b_A)$ tells us the proportions of dark ($B$) and light test test test test test test test test test aa $(\neg B)$ within each column. We could just as well have factored by $B$ first: $\bP(A,B) = \bP(B) \bP( A \mid B)\ .$ Then we Visualizing probabilities in a square is neat because we can draw simple pictures corresponding to interesting facts about our probability distribution.
